Wash and dry produce. Core, deseed, and dice @bell pepper{1}(diced into ½-inch pieces). Peel @sweet potato{1}(diced into ½-inch pieces) if desired. Peel and mince @garlic{1%clove}(minced) and @ginger{1%thumb}(peeled and minced). Halve, peel, and finely dice half the @onion{1}(finely diced). Zest and quarter @lime{1}(zested and quartered).

In a #small bowl{}, combine @cornstarch{1%tablespoon} with 1 TBSP water (2 TBSP for 4). Set aside.

Heat a drizzle of @cooking oil{2%teaspoon} in a large #pot{} over medium-high heat. Add bell pepper and sweet potato; season with ¼ tsp @salt{1/4%tsp} and @pepper{}. Cook, stirring occasionally, until lightly browned, ~{4-6%minutes}.

Stir in @riced cauliflower{6%ounce} until incorporated. Transfer to a #plate{}.

Heat a drizzle of oil in same pot over medium-high heat. Add garlic, ginger, and onion. Cook, stirring, until fragrant, ~{1-2%minutes}.

Add @ground turkey{10%ounce} to pot with aromatics. Cook, breaking up meat into pieces, until browned and cooked through, ~{4-6%minutes}. Season with @curry powder{1%tablespoon}, ¼ tsp salt, and pepper.

Thoroughly shake @coconut milk{1%unit} in container before opening.

Transfer veggies to pot with turkey mixture. Stir in @chicken stock concentrate{3}, cornstarch mixture, coconut milk, @sweet Thai chili sauce{1%ounce}, 1 1/2 cups water (3 cups for 4 servings), and @sugar{1%tablespoon}. Bring to a boil, then reduce to a low simmer. Cook until flavors meld and sweet potato is tender, ~{4-5%minutes}.

> If soup seems too thick, add more water a splash at a time as needed.

Stir juice from two lime wedges into soup. Season with salt and pepper to taste.

Divide between #bowls{}. Garnish with lime zest to taste. Serve with any remaining lime wedges on the side.

> Ground Turkey is fully cooked when internal temperature reaches 165°.